    <div class="not-ai-block">
        <div class="na-label">On the Record — What This Is</div>
        <p><strong>SalvageBotX™ is not an AI product dressed up as software. It is not a chatbot with a logo. It is not a wrapper around a language model pretending to do analysis.</strong> It is a local-execution, deterministic code analysis and productization engine. It runs on your machine. It processes your files. It produces structured, ranked, reproducible output — the same output every time on the same input. No cloud dependency. No inference model. No black box. <strong>It does exactly what the documentation says it does, because it is actual software, not a statistical approximation of software.</strong></p>
    </div>

    <!-- WHY I BUILT THIS -->
    <div class="section-block">
        <div class="sb-label">Origin</div>
        <h2>Why This Exists</h2>
        <p>Every developer has a graveyard. Abandoned projects, half-finished utilities, scripts that solved a real problem once and then got buried under the next sprint. That code has value. It already solved something. Someone else almost certainly has the same problem and would pay to not solve it from scratch.</p>
        <p>SalvageBotX™ was built to stop that value from disappearing. <strong>You feed it a codebase — any codebase, any language, any state of completion — and it tells you exactly what you have, what it is worth, who would buy it, and how to package it for sale.</strong> Not as a suggestion. As a ranked execution plan with price ranges, assembly instructions, and audience profiles.</p>
        <p>The model I built it around is simple: <strong>nothing is wasted.</strong> Even dead code has components that are alive. SalvageBotX™ finds them.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- WHAT IT DOES -->
    <div class="section-block">
        <div class="sb-label">Product Overview</div>
        <h2>What SalvageBotX™ Does</h2>
        <p>SalvageBotX™ ingests any codebase and produces a ranked, itemized execution plan identifying every component that can be extracted, packaged, and sold as a standalone digital product. All processing is local. Nothing leaves your machine.</p>

        <div class="pipeline">
